## Summary of Bill Sections (H.R. 1)

Here's a breakdown of the changes outlined in each section of the bill, as requested:

**Sec. 90001. Border Infrastructure and Wall System.** This section appropriates $46,550,000,000 to the Commissioner of U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) for fiscal year 2025, available until September 30, 2029, to fund border infrastructure projects. These funds will be used for constructing new or improving existing barriers (primary, waterborne, and secondary), building access roads, installing technology like cameras and sensors, and preparing ground for CBP operations. The appropriation comes from the Treasury's general fund.

**Sec. 90002. U.S. Customs and Border Protection Personnel, Fleet Vehicles, and Facilities.**  An additional $4,100,000,000 is allocated to CBP for fiscal year 2025 (until September 30, 2029) for hiring and training additional Border Patrol agents, Office of Field Operations officers, Air and Marine agents, and support personnel.  $2,052,630,000 is provided for recruitment, performance, and retention bonuses for these agents, while $855,000,000 is for vehicle repair and acquisition, and $5,000,000,000 is for facility improvements.  Crucially, funds cannot be used to hire personnel specifically for processing coordinator duties after October 31, 2028.

**Sec. 90003. Detention Capacity.** This section appropriates $45,000,000,000 to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) for fiscal year 2025 (until September 30, 2029) to increase detention capacity for single adult aliens and families.  Aliens can be detained pending removal decisions, and detention standards for single adults are left to the discretion of the Secretary of Homeland Security.  "Family residential centers" are defined as facilities for detaining families encountered by DHS, excluding unaccompanied alien children.

**Sec. 90004. Border Security, Technology, and Screening.** CBP receives an additional $6,168,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 (until September 30, 2029) for border security enhancements. This includes funding for nonintrusive inspection equipment, air and marine operations upgrades, surveillance technology, and the biometric entry/exit system.  Funds are also allocated for screening entrants and initial screenings of unaccompanied alien children, and combating drug trafficking, specifically fentanyl. Surveillance tower procurement is restricted to systems tested and approved by CBP for autonomous capabilities.

**Sec. 90005. State and Local Assistance.**  $500,000,000 is allocated to the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) for State Homeland Security Grant Programs, specifically for detecting and monitoring drones, $625,000,000 for 2026 FIFA World Cup security, and $1,000,000,000 for 2028 Olympics security. An additional $450,000,000 is provided for the Operation Stonegarden Grant Program. A new "State Border Security Reinforcement Fund" is established with $10,000,000,000 (available until September 30, 2034) for states to build border walls, prepare ground for construction, interdict illicit substances, and relocate unlawfully present aliens, with grants available for activities occurring on or after January 20, 2021.

**Sec. 90006. Presidential Residence Protection.**  $300,000,000 is appropriated to FEMA for fiscal year 2025 (until September 30, 2029) to reimburse state and local law enforcement for extraordinary costs associated with protecting residences designated under the Presidential Protection Assistance Act of 1976.  Reimbursement is limited to costs incurred on or after July 1, 2024, exceeding typical law enforcement costs, and directly attributable to Secret Service-requested protection of non-governmental properties.

**Sec. 90007. Department of Homeland Security Appropriations for Border Support.**  An additional $10,000,000,000 is appropriated to the Secretary of Homeland Security for fiscal year 2025 (until September 30, 2029) to reimburse costs incurred in supporting DHS border security missions.

**Sec. 90101. FEHB Improvements.** This section, titled the "FEHB Protection Act of 2025", directs the Director of the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) to verify the legitimacy of qualifying life events used to add family members to the Federal Employees Health Benefits (FEHB) program and to audit family member eligibility. It also allocates $66,000,000 in fiscal year 2026 (available until 2035) for OPM to oversee and audit the FEHB program, including fraud risk assessments.

**Sec. 90102. Pandemic Response Accountability Committee.**  $88,000,000 is appropriated to the Pandemic Response Accountability Committee for fiscal year 2026 (until expended) to oversee the Coronavirus response and funds provided in this Act and other Coronavirus-related legislation.  This section also amends the CARES Act to include this Act in the scope of the Committeeâ€™s oversight and extends the CARES Act oversight period to 2034.

**Sec. 90103. Appropriation for the Office of Management and Budget.**  $100,000,000 is appropriated to the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) for fiscal year 2025 (until September 30, 2029) to identify budget and accounting efficiencies within the executive branch.
